recordings.file-name: XC568909-crystallised song from a male Blackcap Lee Road 15th June 2020_HH_1.mp3
recordings.rmk:
Crystallised song from an unseen presumed male Eurasian Blackcap on territory. For some reason, after many birds having become more quiet in recent weeks, there seemed to be a lot more song from this species on this date. Some fledged juveniles were seen and heard, and it may be that the species at least attempts to raise a second brood more regularly than the literature would suggest, with an associated rise in song from paired males? It may even be that an increased incidence of second broods might be a major driving factor behind the marked increase in breeding numbers of this species in much of at least western Europe?

recordings.rmk:
The song I recorded was sung by a small gray bird (something like a blue tit in size, only with much duller plumage). The bird has a funny way of moving from tree to tree. It sings almost all day long. It prefers to hide, so it's really difficult to see. When I first recorded it, it was singing high in an oak tree. After it spotted me, it flew into a nearby bush and continued to sing. It seems to have different singing places, which is visits according to a certain routine. It also seems to have favorite spots.
The weather was fair (sunny), and the temperature was 25C.

recordings.rmk: Atypical and aberrant Blackcap song with repetition.  Bird singing from dense canopy for 7 minutes whilst observed. Multiple records made in same period all showing same repetition.  Blackcap are very common in this area, no similar repetition has been observed in other individuals.
MixPre 3 II / SennheiserME66-K6 ; High Pass Filter 1500Hz 6db

As I took this in raw video then converted to MP4, it required a further recording off my laptop with an external microphone. I clipped out two intervals of a few moments when only background species was singing. At 44 seconds I begin the next series of calls/song/mimicry. Jumpy sound 50 to 53, then 54 to the end is all pure.

This Blackcap was very hard to see, ranged from 3m to 10m in tall Willow and riverside vegetation, unlike most Blackcap it rarely showed itself at all. The site is nearby to a sewage works and Strawberry farm.

It was an obvious male bird the 'black cap' visible on the 3 occasions I did get brief views and I saw it singing, so there is no doubt it was this bird singing. This is the second Blackcap in 3 years singing with no discernible traditional Blackcap notes, a bird at Binfield sang last year and this year, but was nothing like this bird.

Present for it’s third day two other observers had tried to see the bird without success, the early morning check on my part paid off, but it soon became hard to see after 06:10. No playback was used.

Is it coincidence the Blackcap in Binfield was also nearly impossible to see, are these birds using 100% mimicry? or have they developed a unique set of calls, there was a huge mobile tower within 120m are they affected by mobile equipment?
High-pass filtered (500Hz, 6dB)

recordings.rmk: A short clip from a recently arrived migrant that, over the course of the previous two or three days, was broadcasting from a regular territory of tall scrub and light woodland (mainly sycamore).  I regard the clip as a good example of Blackcap's default song: each verse is 5-7 seconds long. Once rival males arrive in the same vicinity, the song changes. It can become longer, different motifs may be woven into the content (and others that were regular may be omitted) and examples of mimicry might also feature. To listen to a Blackcap singing at its testosterone-drenched peak, try this: XC552441.

It shouldn't be hard but i'm suddenly filled with doubts about my Blackcap-song-recognition skills. There's been a male Blackcap  in my area since end of december. I've seen it a few times when it foraged in my little garden while singing/calling...as Blackcap do.
Now i heard a morning song of what i thought was Blackcap. I've added the record to waarneming.nl and added a bad soundclip (not this one). I received two comments about the record and the recording. Now I'm uploading this to get it out of the way. 

The Blackcap is in the area no doubt about that, but is this song Blackcap or a Robin that maybe only to me sounds like Blackcap? Mind you: it's the end of winter here and only a few hardy Blackcap remain in the country.


Hope to hear from you,
cheers,

Gerben

Mimic of Acrocephalus - at 11sec not a mimic but odd call from resting common starling (Sturnus vulgaris)
Also Nemobius sylvestris cricket in the background. High-pass filter (1500Hz, 6dB)
